{"aligned_page": 5, "alignment_score": null, "char_end_0based": 1480, "char_start_0based": 58, "clean_redaction_id": null, "decision": "excluded", "failed_tests": ["full_page_or_admin"], "original_redaction_id": 7, "page_tag": "[PAGE 05]", "pair_key": "3156606_CIA-RDP79T00975A005700300001-5", "recut_action": "kept_after_recut", "recut_from_original": true, "recut_reason": "noncontent_map_legend_reference", "red_gap_text": "", "red_gap_token_count": 0, "red_source_page": null, "row_kind": "unred_only", "segment_id": 2, "tests": {"full_page_or_admin": {"details": {"alignment_score": null, "candidate_token_total": 237, "coverage": 1.0, "red_admin_stub": true, "red_token_count": 0, "row_kind": "unred_only", "thresholds": {"full_page_coverage": 0.95, "low_alignment_score": 0.25, "min_full_page_tokens": 50}, "unred_token_count": 237}, "passed": false}, "noncontent_keyword": {"details": {"admin_token_ratio": 0.017544, "date_only": false, "has_measurement": false, "has_route_pair": false, "has_weird_map_line_symbol": false, "map_hint_count": 0, "map_legend_like": false, "matched_map_phrases": [], "matched_phrases": [], "near_page_edge": true, "recut_reason": "noncontent_map_legend_reference", "removed_by_recut": false, "short_numeric_or_garbled": false, "short_section_heading": false}, "passed": true}, "nonempty_redacted_alternate_conflict": {"details": {"conflict_reasons": [], "page_candidate_coverage": 1.0, "red_gap_text": "", "red_gap_token_count": 0, "thresholds": {"alternate_length_multiplier": 3, "long_alternate_min_red_gap_tokens": 20, "near_full_page_coverage": 0.9, "short_candidate_max_tokens": 10, "short_span_max_tokens": 5, "short_span_nontrivial_alternate_min_red_gap_tokens": 2}, "token_count": 228}, "passed": true}, "ocr_equivalent_to_redacted_text": {"details": {"length_ratio": null, "reason": "missing_red_gap", "red_gap_text": "", "similarity": null}, "passed": true}, "short_span_min_tokens": {"details": {"min_tokens": 2, "token_count": 228}, "passed": true}}, "text": "Laos. Separate political and military talks between the royal government, the Pathet Lao, and the Souvanna Phouma group began at Namone on 29 May, following agreement to establish a military subcommittee. At the apparent insistence of the Pathet Lao, the \"duties and policies\" of a coalition government will be taken up first in the political talks, beginning with the 31 May session. Discussion of this item of the agenda is likely to be time consuming and will offer the Pathet Lao full scope for raising extraneous issues and for using the talks as a propaganda vehicle. For the parallel military talks, a four-point agenda was adopted relating to maintenance of the cease-fire and collaboration with the ICC.\n\nThe military situation remains generally quiet, although scattered guerrilla activity continues to be reported. The lull in the fighting in the Pa Dong area, apparently stemming from temporary depletion of the Communists' artillery ammunition stocks, persisted through 29 May. Souvanna and Souphannouvong are reported to have voiced no objection to the proposed ICC inspection of the Pa Dong front during a recent interview with ICC Chairman Sen in Xieng Khouang; however, they stated that they would have to \"study\" the matter before giving a formal reply, a tactic calculated to give their forces additional time in which to capture Pa Dong.\n\nBloc airlift operations continue to be scheduled through 30 May", "token_count": 228, "token_end_0based": 235, "token_start_0based": 8, "token_text": "laos separate political and military talks between the royal government the pathet lao and the souvanna phouma group began at namone on 29 may following agreement to establish a military subcommittee at the apparent insistence of the pathet lao the duties and policies of a coalition government will be taken up first in the political talks beginning with the 31 may session discussion of this item of the agenda is likely to be time consuming and will offer the pathet lao full scope for raising extraneous issues and for using the talks as a propaganda vehicle for the parallel military talks a four-point agenda was adopted relating to maintenance of the cease-fire and collaboration with the icc the military situation remains generally quiet although scattered guerrilla activity continues to be reported the lull in the fighting in the pa dong area apparently stemming from temporary depletion of the communists artillery ammunition stocks persisted through 29 may souvanna and souphannouvong are reported to have voiced no objection to the proposed icc inspection of the pa dong front during a recent interview with icc chairman sen in xieng khouang however they stated that they would have to study the matter before giving a formal reply a tactic calculated to give their forces additional time in which to capture pa dong bloc airlift operations continue to be scheduled through 30 may", "unred_source_page": 5}
